Full Time Work/Studies ( “The Professional” )
Notes
Don’t realize its harder than it seems.
80% have full time jobs or are in school.
Likely to pay for themselves
Many have kids and careers. Following an old dream. getting back into music
Almost none are professional musicians
Anyone with kids really wants to try harder but ‘life gets in the way’. Usually are the best students. Polite. Helpful to others. Mean well.
Not nearly as outgoing as others.
they are most important because they are most likely to afford our prices.
the most important feature we can provide them is the structure and the teacher interaction.
don’t fit in with the younger spastic kids. generational gap in the online community
others are just busy.
People get overwhelmed.
fulfilling a dream - artistic endeavor. already have a job

Advanced User
Notes
We do not address the needs of advanced users.
we need to service more advanced users who are not newbies. the majority of them know the basics.
We only offer comprehensive courses. Advanced users are forced to sit/pay through the early levels
We’d like to appeal to the people who already know their DAW and want to know the nuances.
offer genre specific material. more niche topics
we do offer: video, chat, forum, video feedback (most important to them), hangouts
we should offer: 30 min one-on-ones
we should offer: introductory meeting
we should offer: exit interview
Our classes are VERY expensive. Even 70% of our audience cannot be served by our product. These are 70% of our untapped user base.
We’d like broader, cheaper services.
We’d like to demonstrate value quickly
‘bite-size chunks’ for power users. - don’t want to be spoon fed 6 levels of stuff they already know
may have music career hopes
Not going to spend the money.
Need advanced courses that don’t start from the beginning.
The only thing that stopped assessment tests is logistics and manpower. A good placement test is desirable.
Masterclass by an artist that is shorter than several months would really be appealing. ($500)
More inclined to write in and start off as leads. They want to make sure they don’t pay for things they already know.
They typically ask what’s covered in the course.

Matt’s Notes
More artistic clientele in general
Screening is potentially useful for people that end up knowing all the early stuff. They may get bored and fall off or feel like they overpaid.
‘The Beginner’ and the ‘The person who’s been at it for years’ ARE the people that dubspot services.
pure video is not as valuable as interaction with other students. comments and cohorts are important.
ALWAYS a downward slope in retention.
we don’t have a good communication method.
not enough staff to reach out to those that are slipping.
seems like people do not read the instructions or content. students email everyone questions right away.
first weeks are brutal for teachers. (high participation, bad assignments, have to help operate DSO
difficult to get new students acclimated to open courses. a sort of guidance counselor would help
there are people that need structure and accountability. can’t just watch videos alone.
In general, students trail off over time.
Completely brand new to production (15%)
DSO is seen as a 'gym membership'. Start off gung-ho and then life gets in the way
For a lot of students classes are too intense
They trust us to provide.
Short courses. (1hr - 3hrs)
genre specific and more advanced in general
Begin learning at whatever experience level you’re currently at.
‘the vault’
high production videos.
we’re ‘cool’
we have name recognition, trust.
professional instructors.
teachers get burnt out with customer service requests

Hart’s Notes
Not a lot clear difference between the DJs and production students.
Production is more or less synonymous with DJing.
Some people want to perform.
DSO is a slightly older demographic.
NYC students are a younger demographic.
Our marketing is targeted towards more advanced, scene users.
DJing is really about doing and reading crowds so its not teachable past a certain point.
40/50% of purchases are made by parents
We leave people with finished music. results are tangible
We teach the artistic element, as opposed to college where courses are more geared towards engineering and the technical details.
Leads have the money to spend and want to ask questions
We offer weekend workshops.
We should lead genre specific workshops. Good upsetting opportunity, hits many topics that we offer.
International students don’t end up signing up for master programs because their visas don’t allow them to stay past 6 months.
We cannot give people education visas because we are not accredited.
A lot of people ask about scholarships, financial aid, and the GI bill. Since we are not accredited, we cannot offer these. These people usually end up not signing up.
20% know what course they want to take.
30% “ i want to learn how to dj/produce. what sort of classes do you have?”
1. dub step, trap, progressive house, trance,
2. hip-hop, techno, house
3. singer-songwriters who want to produce for themselves
In january we had 760 leads come in.
Weekly number of leads is about 100-150 people a week. (phone calls, tours, emails)
